ipt transmission, and the reasons for its success, for example among monasteries belonging to the Cistercian order in southern Germany. Damien Kempf is Lecturer in Medieval History at the University of Liverpool; Marcus Bull is Andrew W. Mellon Distinguished Professor of Medieval and Early Modern Studies at the University of North Carolina, Chapel Hill.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aChurch historyyMiddle Ages, 600-1500. 0aCrusadesyFirst, 1096-1099vSources. 4aBibliography & Manuscripts. 4aMedieval History. 4aMedieval Literature. 4aMilitary History. 7aHISTORY / Medieval.2bisacsh  aCistercian order.  aCrusades.  aFirst Crusade.  aHistoria Iherosolimitana.  aRobert the Monk.  aauthor's identity.  acritical edition.  acrusaders' exploits.  aliterary retellings.  amanuscript copies.  amanuscript transmission.  amedieval "bestseller".  asouthern Germany.  asuccess.  atwelfth century.1 aBull, M.G., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKempf, D., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978178204078140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781782040781423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781782040781/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles